## Architecture

### Core Elements

#### Drupal

- Mature CMS acting as primary data source
- Provides GraphQL APIs for structured content
- Configured as backend for articles, pages, editorial content

#### Ring Publishing

- Cloud-based digital publishing platform
- Alternative CMS data source (until migration completes)
- APIs expose editorial content and metadata

**Useful Links:**

- [Ring Publishing Website](https://ringpublishing.com/)
- [Ring Publishing Help Documentation](https://help.ringpublishing.com/)
- [Ring Publishing Developer Documentation](https://developer.ringpublishing.com/)
- [Ring Publishing RMS Console](https://rms-console.ringpublishing.com/spaces)
- [Content API v2 Documentation](https://developer.ringpublishing.com/docs/ContentAPI/v2/index.html)
- [Content API Playground](https://api.ringpublishing.com/content/v2)
- [Websites API v2 Documentation](https://developer.ringpublishing.com/docs/WebsitesAPI/v2/index.html)
- [Websites API Playground](https://api.ringpublishing.com/websites/v2)

#### Configuration

- Object defining how a publication is set up
- Specifies data sources, content types, settings, features
- Validated using Zod schemas
- Isolated per publication for flexibility

#### Connector

- Central decision-making layer
- Switches between data sources (Drupal, Ring Publishing) based on configuration
- Orchestrates requests to appropriate gateway
- Keeps front-end agnostic of data source

#### Gateway

- Dedicated access layer for each data source
- Handles communication logic (authentication, query building, API requests)
- Each CMS has its own gateway (Drupal Gateway, Ring Publishing Gateway)
- Acts as adapters for external CMS APIs

#### Mapper

- Transforms raw data from data sources into standardized format
- Normalizes field names, structures, nested data
- Validates using Zod schemas after transformation
- Creates bridge between heterogeneous CMS data models and unified representation

#### Components

- Astro.js front-end building blocks
- Render validated content into pages
- Work independently of data source
- Connected with Firma's design system
- Reusable UI elements

---

## Security & Secrets

### Secrets Management

- **Storage:** AWS Secrets Manager
- **Types:**
  - **Common secrets:** Used by all apps
  - **App-specific secrets:** Used by single app
- **Naming convention:** `orbit/<env>/<common|<app>>`
  - Examples:
    - `orbit/develop/common` - All apps on development
    - `orbit/stage/tele.ch` - tele.ch on stage

⚠️ **IMPORTANT:** Secrets defined on `RMS Orbit (test)` and `RMS Orbit (prod)` must also be defined on `RMS Orbit (stg)` environment! Otherwise PRs pointing to other environments than `stage` won't be able to load secrets and instances might fail.

### AWS Authentication

Before accessing SSM secrets (e.g. for local dev or builds that require secrets), you must authenticate first:

```bash
aws_login <env>   # e.g. aws_login develop, aws_login stage, aws_login prod
```

### Using Secrets

- Loaded within `init-envs.ts` middleware (injected on each request)
- Available under `process.env.ORBIT_SECRET_KEYS`

### Security Guidelines

1. **Access Control:** Default deny approach to sensitive data
2. **Error Handling:** Log all failures, exceptions, errors on trusted system
3. **System Configuration:** Keep systems updated, remove unnecessary components
4. **Cryptographic Practices:** Use modern algorithms, store keys/secrets/passwords in AWS Secrets Manager
5. **Input Validation:** Validate all untrusted inputs, use standard routines for output encoding
6. **Threat Modeling:** Keep security considerations in mind when planning tasks
7. **Dependencies:** Use Snyk to check for vulnerabilities

---

## Coding Standards

### Priorities (In Order)

When implementing or reviewing code, follow these priorities:

1. **Is it secure?** - "Do we introduce new possible vulnerabilities?"
2. **Is it functional?** - "Does it do what it's expected to do?"
3. **Is it maintainable?** - "Are there side effects? Is it clean and structured? Does it follow DRY and KISS? Are tests implemented?"
4. **Is it fast?** - "Is it optimized for performance?"
5. **Is it compliant?** - "Does it comply with our coding standards?"

### Definition of Done

Ensure these five core pillars are fulfilled:

1. **Security** - No new vulnerabilities introduced
2. **Functionality** - Performs as expected
3. **Maintainability** - Clean, structured, DRY, KISS, tested
4. **Performance** - Optimized
5. **Compliance** - Follows coding standards

### Code Review Guidelines

- Review code thoroughly and understand **all** changes
- Test it
- Check test files and documentation
- Follow the same priorities listed above

### Performance Guidelines

- Avoid unnecessary logic and assets
- **Only ship what's needed**
- Avoid unnecessary re-renderings
- Static implementations are always faster and less error-prone
- Consider lazy loading for code, stylesheets, HTML
- Evaluate if dependencies can be removed or simplified

### ESLint Rules

Key rules enforced:

- `import/order` - Enforces import ordering (see [Import Order](#import-order))
- `import/no-cycle` - Prevents circular dependencies
- `import/no-unresolved` - Warns on unresolved imports
- `@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars` - Warns on unused variables (allows `_` prefix)
- `no-nested-ternary` - Error on nested ternaries
- `import/namespace` - Off (ts-pattern throws errors)

**Relaxed rules for:**

- `apps/spotlight.rms.rocks/**/*` - `import/no-unresolved` and `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` are off
- `*/**/generated.ts` - `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` and `@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars` are off

### TypeScript

- Use proper typings
- Avoid `any` unless in generated files or spotlight.rms.rocks
- Use `_` prefix for intentionally unused variables/args

